  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Settlement is the day money changes hands and the title transfers from the seller to the buyer. The settlement date is set in the contract and confirmed by both solicitors in the days leading up. In the overwhelming majority of Queensland transactions, settlement happens on the agreed day, the funds are exchanged, and both parties move on. But occasionally one or both parties fail to complete, and the contract steps in to determine what happens next.</p>

      <p>Settlement default is the formal term for this failure. It can take several forms: the buyer does not present the balance of funds, the seller does not deliver the title in the form required, or some combination of unresolved issues prevents the transfer being completed. The standard REIQ contract used for most Brisbane sales sets out a structured process for what happens after default. Understanding that process before settlement, rather than during a crisis, gives both parties more options if something does go wrong.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The legal framework: time of the essence</h2>
      <p>Under the standard REIQ contract, time is not strictly of the essence at the original settlement date. That sounds counterintuitive, but it matters legally. If the original date passes without settlement, neither party can immediately terminate the contract on the spot. What they can do is issue a notice to complete. Once that notice is issued, time is of the essence at the new date specified in the notice (commonly 14 days). After that notice period, the innocent party can terminate the contract and pursue damages.</p>

      <p>This two-stage process is deliberately designed to prevent immediate contract collapse over short delays. A buyer whose lender is one day late, or a seller whose mortgage discharge document is held up by the bank, has time to fix the issue without losing the deal. The 14 day notice period gives both sides the chance to settle before the contract breaks down.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common causes of buyer default</h2>
      <p>Most buyer defaults trace back to the financier. Even after a contract has gone unconditional and finance has been approved, settlement requires the lender to actually be ready to fund on the day. The most common buyer default scenarios are: finance falling through at the last moment because the bank has reassessed the borrower or the property valuation, loan documents not being executed and returned in time for the bank to release funds, the buyer's solicitor not receiving cleared funds from the buyer in time to deposit them with the seller's solicitor, and a change in the buyer's circumstances (job loss, relationship breakdown, illness) between unconditional and settlement.</p>

      <p>A smaller category of buyer defaults are tactical: the buyer has reconsidered, found the property has issues they did not previously know about, or is using the threat of default to renegotiate. These are rare but not unheard of, and they tend to play out very differently from genuine financial defaults.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common causes of seller default</h2>
      <p>Seller defaults usually relate to clearing the title. The most common scenarios are: the mortgage discharge has not been arranged in time, meaning the lender is not ready to release the title at settlement, rates, water, or land tax clearance certificates have not been obtained from the relevant authorities, a caveat or third party interest on title has not been resolved, an unresolved matrimonial property order or other legal restriction is preventing transfer, and (less commonly) the seller has had a change of heart and is trying to delay or terminate.</p>

      <p>Most seller defaults are administrative rather than deliberate. The remedy in nearly all cases is for the seller's solicitor to push the relevant party (the bank, the council, the state revenue office) to complete the outstanding step quickly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The first response: notice to complete</h2>
      <p>When a party fails to settle on the agreed day, the innocent party's solicitor issues a notice to complete. This is a formal written notice that the contract has not been performed and that the defaulting party has a specified period (commonly 14 days, occasionally shorter or longer depending on the contract terms) to cure the default and complete the transaction. The notice triggers time becoming of the essence: missing the new deadline gives the innocent party the right to terminate.</p>

      <p>During the notice period, the contract remains alive. The defaulting party can still settle, the innocent party is required to remain ready to complete, and both solicitors continue to work toward closing the deal. In most cases, the cause of default is resolved within the notice period and settlement occurs at the new date.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">If the default is cured within the notice period</h2>
      <p>When settlement occurs at the new date, the contract is performed and the transaction completes. The defaulting party, however, is typically liable for the innocent party's reasonable costs of the delay and for penalty interest on the unpaid amount.</p>

      <p>Penalty interest is a contract term, set as a rate per annum on the outstanding contract price (or the deposit amount, depending on which party defaulted and which version of the contract was used). The rate is commonly in the range of 8 to 12 per cent per annum, calculated daily on the period of delay. On a $1.2 million purchase delayed by 10 days at 10 per cent, the penalty interest would be roughly $3,300. Not catastrophic, but not trivial either.</p>

      <p>Innocent party costs can include additional bridging finance interest if the seller has already committed to a new property and is carrying two mortgages, additional rent or storage if the buyer is between properties, and the legal costs of issuing the notice and managing the dispute. These costs are settled at or after the new settlement date, often by deduction from the funds being transferred.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">If the default is not cured</h2>
      <p>If the defaulting party fails to settle within the notice period, the innocent party can elect to terminate the contract. Termination has different consequences depending on which side defaulted.</p>

      <p>If the buyer defaults: the seller can keep the deposit (typically 10 per cent of the contract price, held in trust by the agent), claim damages for any additional loss, and put the property back on the market. If the property is then resold for less than the original contract price, the seller can claim the difference from the defaulting buyer in addition to the deposit forfeit, less any reasonable resale costs.</p>

      <p>If the seller defaults: the buyer can claim the deposit back, claim damages for any additional costs incurred (legal costs, bridging finance, lost rental income on a sold property they were vacating), and pursue specific performance if they want to force the sale to proceed. Specific performance is a court order requiring the seller to complete the contract. It is rarely sought because the practical and legal cost is high, but the option exists.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Damages: what can be claimed</h2>
      <p>Damages aim to put the innocent party in the position they would have been in if the contract had completed as agreed. The categories that commonly arise are: additional bridging finance or interest costs caused by the delay, additional rent or accommodation costs, additional storage or moving costs, the difference between the contract price and the resale price (if the seller had to remarket), legal and incidental costs incurred because of the default, and lost rental income or occupancy benefit during the delay.</p>

      <p>Damages do not usually include pure inconvenience or stress (those are non-recoverable in contract law absent a specific clause), and they are subject to reasonable mitigation. The innocent party cannot let costs run up indefinitely; they must take reasonable steps to reduce their loss.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How sellers minimise default risk</h2>
      <p>The single biggest factor in avoiding seller default is the solicitor's preparation in the two to three weeks before settlement. Practical steps that consistently reduce risk: instruct the solicitor early to begin the mortgage discharge process, with a target of having discharge documents ready a week before settlement, obtain rates, water, and land tax clearance certificates as soon as the contract is unconditional rather than waiting until the final week, resolve any title issues (caveats, easements, third party interests) at the earliest opportunity, and confirm with the solicitor in writing 7 to 10 days before settlement that all outstanding items are on track to complete.</p>

      <p>If the seller has any concerns about the buyer's likelihood of settling on the day, raise them with the solicitor early. The seller cannot directly investigate the buyer's finance position, but the solicitors can communicate, and the agent can often pick up signals from the buyer or the buyer's broker about whether things are tracking.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">If the seller suspects the buyer will default</h2>
      <p>The standard advice if you suspect the other side will default is to act through your solicitor and not directly. Raise the concern early, get advice on options, and avoid public statements that could undermine the sale or expose the seller to defamation or breach of confidence claims. If a backup offer exists, the agent should be ready to engage with the backup buyer the moment the primary contract terminates.</p>

      <p>It is also worth thinking through the practical steps of returning the property to market: refreshing the photography or marketing copy if needed, coordinating with the agent on positioning ("recently terminated" rather than "vendor desperate"), and being ready to act quickly if termination becomes necessary. A property that comes back on market within days of termination, with a clear narrative about why, typically resells well. A property that drags through a slow termination process and reappears weeks later, looking distressed, attracts opportunistic offers.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">PEXA and electronic settlement</h2>
      <p>Most Queensland settlements are now conducted electronically through PEXA, the property exchange platform. PEXA reduces some traditional default risks: there are no more lost cheques, mis-routed bank transfers, or settlement clerks stuck in traffic. The funds and title transfer happen simultaneously through the platform, with all parties locked in digitally.</p>

      <p>PEXA has introduced its own narrow set of risks: digital signing failures, system outages, and the requirement that all parties' representatives be online and ready at the scheduled time. These issues are typically resolved within hours rather than days, and PEXA itself has well-developed protocols for handling outages. The net effect of PEXA has been to reduce the rate of settlement defaults in Queensland and to make the resolution of administrative issues quicker than in the paper era.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What not to do if the other party defaults</h2>
      <p>Three things to avoid if you find yourself on the innocent side of a default: do not take unilateral action. Refusing to release keys, trying to keep funds, or making your own decisions about what should happen next will almost always be the wrong move and may expose you to your own breach claim. Act through your solicitor and follow the contract.</p>

      <p>Do not publicly accuse the other party. Even if the other party has clearly breached, statements made publicly about their conduct can attract defamation risk, especially if your characterisation turns out to be inaccurate or overreaching. Channel everything through the solicitors.</p>

      <p>Do not rush the decision to terminate. Termination is a one-way door. Once the contract is terminated, it cannot be revived without both parties' agreement. If there is any reasonable prospect of the default being cured, let the notice process play out. Many defaults that look catastrophic on day one are resolved by day seven.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>Settlement default is rare. In a typical year, only a small percentage of contracts that go unconditional fail to settle on time, and most of those that do default settle within the notice period. The contract is designed to absorb short delays without breaking, and the legal framework gives both sides time to resolve issues before the deal collapses.</p>

      <p>The most important factor in avoiding default is solicitor preparation in the lead-up to settlement. The most important factor in handling default well, if it does occur, is acting through the solicitor, following the contract process, and keeping options open. Sellers and buyers who understand this framework before signing a contract are far better placed to handle the rare case where settlement does not go to plan.</p>

